I bought these when they were on sale. I got it for a little over $16.00. I was looking for a headphone that was white, looked good, but would not break the bank. This Sony headphone fitted the bill perfectly. The little red you see on the headphone...(read full review) I bought these when they were on sale. I got it for a little over $16.00. I was looking for a headphone that was white, looked good, but would not break the bank. This Sony headphone fitted the bill perfectly. The little red you see on the headphone is to let users know that is the right side. On the left side there is a little tactile dot, so you can put these things on correctly without visibility. To me it w ... as just icing on the cake. The base is on the average, but I came from some high bass in the ear headphones, so I immediately noticed the difference. These headphones bleed out sound, which for me is a double edged sword. I can wrap the headphones around my neck and pump the music. But, this can also bother others around you. These headphones are a little tight and there is no cushion on the band so it does begin to hurt a little if worn for about an hour. I actually ran with these. They have been ok so far, but I do not recommend them because they will shift around on your head. These were not marketed for athletic use, so I'm not angry about it. The quality and construction of the headphones are fairly robust. The cups in comparison to say Dr. Dre Beats Monster. The Monsters are thinner, but at about $200 price tag, it is comparing apples and oranges. I'm just giving a reference. Compared to a $200 studio headphone there is no comparison. People that say they are as good...umm no comment. The 3.5 mm jack is not gold plated and the cord is big and flat. This helps to keep it from getting tangled, and it feels much more robust. The name Sony speaks for itself. Sony typically does not make junk and this is no exception. I expect these headphones to go through a beating and last. expand » « collapse

Item.Item: Sony MDR ZX100/WHI - headphones - Ear-cup, Binaural - White
Item.Review:
Pros: Cheap, okay sound quality, sleek/ stylish, blocks most outside noise
Cons: Not for people who expect a lot of bass, not very loud
This review is based on my experiences with other similarly priced headphones at comparable price ranges ($10-$40).
First off, for only $20, I wasn't expecting these headphones to completely blow my mind. And they didn't, but perhaps it's just because I have too high of expectations for sound quality.
These headphones instantly caught my eye at the store with their sleek, milk-white color, urban feel, and attractive price. After reading several positive reviews from many different websites, I decided to give this product a try. They seemed like they would produce a satisfactory sound just from the looks. However, for on-the-ear ... headphones, the bass was seriously lacking. With drivers larger than most regular headphones, I would think there would be a little more bass response from the music. Nevertheless, the sound remains tinny and flat (like the headphones included with an iPhone or iPod) even when using the "Bass Booster" EQ on my iPhone. Volume levels were also pretty low, which isn't much of an issue for me since I don't listen to my music very loud. Yet, I was able to turn my iPhone's volume all the way up, though, and still feel a somewhat lacking audible level. As for comfort, I only wore these for about ten minutes (while testing their sound quality), but they were perfect on the comfort scale for me: not too tight, not too loose, soft on the ears, easily adjustable, and very lightweight.
There really wasn't anything amazing about these headphones that didn't keep me from returning them and purchasing something different. I took them back to Best Buy and instead bought some IN-ear Altec headphones (that literally crush these in sound quality and bass reproduction- and they're the exact same price). I am very satisfied with my decision to do this. I was really disappointed in these headphones because the sound quality wasn't anywhere near what I had preferred, plus I haven't found any other headphones that look this stylish and sleek, for such a great pri ... expand » « collapse

I got some Sony headphones free from a rewards program that were much better as far as ear comfort (oval instead of round earphones), but they broke less than a year of ownership from cheap materials. I told my mom that I would like some new headphones for my birthday, but I did not want the Sony brand because you cannot tell how tight they will be. My dad bought these headphones anyway from Best Buy. I tried them just in case they were any different since they were a different model number and ... they were worse than the ones I currently own. Mine have stretched out so they are not as bad as they used to be. I would never be able to wear these more than 5 minutes at a time because they cause ear pain right when you put them on.
